x4freetext: .Back-to-back foils of Pu-239 and B-10 or Li-6 were
used in measurements 1-3. The Pu-239 layer was
prepared by electrospraying of plutonium acetate on
an Al disk. Its thickness was 248 micrograms/cm**2.
.The B-10 layer was prepared by evaporating elemental
boron under vacuum. In this way a homogeneous layer
with a thickness of 184 micro-gram/cm**2 and
.The Li-6 consisted of a (Li-6)-F layer also prepared
by vacuum evaporation. Its thickness was 89.7 micro-
.All layers were deposited onto 0.1 mm thick aluminium
Pu-239 target was used with a total mass of 12 grams
were done. The first three measurements were done
with back-to-back foils of Pu-239 and Li-6
or B-10 (flux monitors), at 45 degrees with respect
to the neutron beam. The shape of the Pu-239 fission
cross section is determined assuming a 1/v-shape for
the Li-6 or B-10 cross sections. The following
1. Using Li-6, energy region 0.022-2.0 eV, LINAC
at 100 Hz, 20 ns pulse width, flight path 9.3 m,
permanent filter , Mn, background filters , Au,
2. Using Li-6, energy region 2 - 5 keV, LINAC
at 800 Hz, 4 ns pulse width, flight path 9.3 m,
3. Using B-10, energy region 0.1 - 30 keV, LINAC
at 800 Hz, 4 ns pulse width, flight path 30 m,
4. A 4-th measurement, U-235 as monitor, flight path
30 m, LINAC at 600 Hz, 24 ns was done using a
liquid scintillator and He-3 spectrometer. These
measurements were done by putting alternatively Pu
resp. U samples in the scintillator. The transmis-
sion through the Pu and U samples was measured
simultaneously with a He-3 gas scintillator.
